const steps = [
  {
    label: 'Run an AI Visibility Audit',
    detail: 'Before changing anything, establish a baseline. Submit 20–40 structured queries to ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini, Copilot, and Google AI Overviews — queries that represent the problems your target audience asks AI engines to solve. Record which brands are cited in each answer, the language used to describe your category, and where your brand appears or is entirely absent. This audit is the single most important deliverable in the entire programme. It tells you which battles to fight, which platforms to prioritise, and where competitor citation share is weakest. Without a baseline, every subsequent optimisation decision is a guess. Document results in a spreadsheet by platform, query, brand mentioned, and description accuracy.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Map Your Brand Entity',
    detail: 'Generative engines do not retrieve pages — they retrieve entities. An entity is your brand as understood by AI models: its name, category membership, key attributes, differentiation claims, and relationships to other entities (industry, product category, geography, founders). Map every attribute your brand entity should carry and then audit how consistently those attributes appear across your website, your structured data, your Google Business Profile, LinkedIn, industry directories, Wikidata, and every third-party mention you can access or influence. Identify contradictions — where your company is described as doing one thing on one platform and something different elsewhere. Every contradiction creates entity ambiguity, and ambiguity makes AI models default to whichever competitor is described most consistently.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Identify Content Gaps',
    detail: 'Cross-reference the queries from your audit against your current content inventory. The gap between what you have published and what AI engines are being asked is your content opportunity map. Prioritise in three tiers: first, queries where competitors are being cited and you are absent (displacement opportunities); second, queries where no brand holds citation share (first-mover opportunities); third, queries where your brand is mentioned but inaccurately described (accuracy remediation). Displacement opportunities typically show faster results because the query pattern already produces citations — you are redirecting existing AI behaviour, not establishing new citation behaviour from scratch. First-mover opportunities take longer to show results but produce durable citation share once established.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Build Citation Architecture',
    detail: 'Citation architecture is how your content is structured to be maximally extractable by large language models. Every page needs four components: a definitional opening (one to two sentences that answer the primary query directly and completely); short, single-point paragraphs of two to four sentences each; a FAQ section that matches the exact phrasing of queries submitted to AI engines; and tables or lists that can be read as standalone data units without surrounding context. Retrofit existing high-priority pages first — the audit will have identified which pages are already close to citation-ready. Then build new content to this architecture from the outset. Pages that bury their main claim after three paragraphs of context-setting will consistently lose citation share to pages that answer first and support second.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Deploy Schema Markup',
    detail: 'Schema markup gives AI crawlers and retrieval systems machine-readable signals about the type, structure, and relationships of your content. Deploy Article schema on every substantive content page with correct datePublished, dateModified, author, and publisher fields. Add FAQPage schema that mirrors your on-page FAQ section exactly. Use HowTo schema on process pages (like this one). Apply Organization schema with complete name, url, logo, and sameAs fields linking to your major profiles. Add BreadcrumbList on all non-homepage pages. Validate every schema deployment using the Google Rich Results Test and the schema.org validator before publishing. Invalid schema is not neutral — it can create conflicting signals that reduce entity resolution accuracy.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Configure Technical GEO Signals',
    detail: 'Technical GEO covers the signals that determine whether AI crawlers can access your content and how retrieval systems interpret your site structure. Check your robots.txt to ensure you are not inadvertently blocking AI crawlers — many sites block GPTBot, ClaudeBot, or PerplexityBot via legacy rules that were never intended to block AI access. Add an llms.txt file at your domain root declaring your site\'s expertise areas, key pages, and content purpose — this is a direct signal to AI systems about how to interpret your content. Consolidate canonical URLs to prevent entity signal fragmentation across duplicate or near-duplicate pages. Ensure your Core Web Vitals scores do not impede crawl budget — slow pages get crawled less frequently, reducing the freshness of your content in retrieval pipelines.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Build Authoritative External Sources',
    detail: 'AI models weight sources by perceived authority. Authority in GEO is built through citation footprint: the volume and quality of authoritative third-party sources that describe your brand correctly and consistently. This means earning editorial mentions in industry publications, contributing expert quotes to category-defining articles, updating or creating a Wikidata entry for your brand, ensuring your brand appears in relevant association directories with accurate attribute data, and building relationships with journalists and analysts who cover your category in publications that feed AI training data and RAG retrieval pipelines. Source building for GEO follows similar principles to link building for SEO — quality and topical relevance matter more than quantity — but the mechanism is different. You are building training data signals and retrieval source authority, not PageRank.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Monitor, Measure, and Iterate',
    detail: 'GEO is a programme, not a project. Set up a weekly monitoring cadence using a fixed query set — typically 30–60 queries that represent your core citation targets — and run it consistently across all five major AI platforms. Log citation frequency (how often your brand is mentioned), brand accuracy (whether descriptions match your entity map), competitor citation share (which competitors are gaining or losing), and answer format changes (whether platforms are switching from cited answers to direct synthesis). Review the data monthly to identify which pages are driving citation improvements, which entity gaps remain, and which source-building targets have produced retrievable mentions. Adjust content, entity signals, and outreach priorities based on what the data shows. The brands that compound GEO gains fastest treat monitoring as a core deliverable, not an optional extra.'
  }
];

const platformData = [
