      <div class="prose-dark">
        <h2 id="what-is-geo" class="anchor-top">What GEO Actually Involves</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Generative engine optimisation (GEO) is the practice of making your brand the cited answer when AI engines respond to queries in your category.</strong> It differs from traditional SEO in its mechanism: instead of optimising for algorithmic ranking signals that drive click-through, GEO optimises for the entity signals, content structure, and source authority that large language models use to select and cite information in their generated answers.
        </p>
        <p>
          Doing GEO means working across three layers simultaneously. The entity layer covers how your brand is defined and described across every platform AI models can access. The content layer covers how your pages are structured to be extractable by retrieval-augmented generation systems. The authority layer covers the citation footprint — editorial mentions, directory listings, structured data — that AI models use to assess whether your brand is a credible source in your category.
        </p>
        <p>
          Many teams attempt GEO by publishing more content or adding schema to existing pages. This produces limited results because it addresses one layer without the others. A brand with excellent content structure but inconsistent entity descriptions will produce citations that misrepresent the brand. A brand with strong entity authority but unstructured content will generate vague mentions without specific citations. All three layers must be addressed for GEO to compound. For a deeper grounding in why this is the case, see the <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">complete guide to generative engine optimisation</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="before-you-start" class="anchor-top">Before You Start</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Attempting GEO without preparation produces wasted effort and misleading data.</strong> Before executing any of the eight steps below, confirm three things: you have access to all five major AI platforms for query testing; you have a structured document for recording audit findings; and you have a clear definition of your brand entity — what your company does, who it serves, and what differentiates it — that all team members will use consistently.
        </p>
        <p>
          The entity definition is particularly important. If different team members describe your brand differently when creating content or updating profiles, you will be building entity inconsistency into the programme from the start. Agree on a canonical one-sentence brand description, a canonical category label, and a canonical set of differentiating attributes before any content or technical work begins. Everything produced in the programme should be traceable back to this entity definition.
        </p>
        <p>
          If your brand is already active in SEO, review your existing schema markup and internal link structure before starting. Some existing technical work will carry over to GEO; other elements — particularly keyword-density-oriented content — may need to be restructured rather than added to. Understanding your starting point prevents duplication and identifies quick wins that can be implemented in the first 30 days. The <a href="/geo-strategy/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO strategy framework</a> gives you the planning structure to sequence this work correctly.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="step-by-step" class="anchor-top">The 8-Step Process</h2>
        <p>
          The eight steps below represent the complete GEO implementation sequence. They are ordered for a reason: each step generates data or structures that the following steps depend on. Skipping ahead — particularly past the audit and entity mapping phases — is the most common reason GEO programmes fail to produce measurable results.
        </p>
      </div>

