            </span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-white">{step.label}</h3>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">{step.detail}</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="content-requirements" class="anchor-top">Content Requirements for GEO</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>GEO-optimised content is structured for extraction, not for engagement.</strong> The distinction matters: content written to attract clicks tends to be narrative, context-rich, and designed to keep readers on the page. Content written for AI citation needs to be immediately extractable — the answer must be accessible in the first sentence, supported by short paragraphs, and labelled with schema that confirms what type of content it is.
        </p>
        <p>
          Every page you produce for GEO should satisfy three tests. First, the extraction test: can the primary answer be lifted from the first two sentences without any surrounding context? Second, the paragraph test: does each paragraph cover exactly one point, stated at the start? Third, the FAQ test: do your on-page FAQ questions match the exact phrasing of queries your audience submits to AI engines, not question phrasing you invented?
        </p>
        <p>
          Failing any of these tests does not mean the page cannot be cited — it means it is less likely to be cited than a competitor page that passes all three. GEO is competitive: when two brands have comparable authority, the one with better citation architecture wins the mention. For a detailed breakdown of specific content patterns that drive citations, see <a href="/geo-best-practices/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO best practices</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="platform-differences" class="anchor-top">Platform-by-Platform Differences</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Each major AI platform uses a different citation mechanism, which means GEO tactics must be calibrated per platform.</strong> A strategy optimised only for Perplexity will underperform on ChatGPT; a strategy built around Google AI Overviews will not transfer directly to Copilot. The table below summarises the key differences.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border hair">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b hair bg-white/[.03]">
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Platform</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Retrieval Mechanism</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Citation Style</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Priority Signal for GEO</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {platformData.map((row, i) => (
              <tr class={i % 2 === 0 ? 'border-b hair' : 'border-b hair bg-white/[.02]'}>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-white">{row.platform}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">{row.mechanism}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">{row.citationStyle}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">{row.prioritySignal}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
        <p>
          The practical implication is that your monitoring query set must be run on all five platforms, not just the one where your audience is most active. Citation behaviour shifts as platforms update their models and retrieval logic. A brand that monitors only Perplexity may be unaware that its Gemini visibility has collapsed — or that it has become the default citation in ChatGPT for its core category queries. Cross-platform monitoring is not optional; it is what makes GEO measurable. For the complete framework behind this approach, see the <a href="/geo-framework/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO framework</a> page.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="measuring-progress" class="anchor-top">Measuring Progress</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>GEO progress is measured by citation frequency, brand accuracy, and cross-platform reach — not by organic sessions or keyword rankings.</strong> These are different metrics measuring a different layer of the search ecosystem. A brand can rank on page one for its target keywords and still be invisible in AI-generated answers; conversely, a brand can gain significant AI citation share without any change in traditional search rankings.
        </p>
        <p>
          Set up a tracking spreadsheet with columns for: platform, query, brand cited (yes/no), brand description accuracy (accurate / partially accurate / inaccurate / absent), competitor mentions, and answer format (cited sources / direct synthesis / no answer). Run this query set weekly. After four to six weeks of consistent data, patterns will emerge: which pages are driving citation improvements, which entity descriptions are persisting, and which platforms are lagging relative to the others.
        </p>
        <p>
          Monthly reviews should produce three outputs: a citation trend report comparing current versus baseline frequency by platform; an entity accuracy report identifying remaining description inconsistencies; and a content iteration list of pages to restructure based on citation data. Quarterly reviews should produce updated priorities for source-building outreach and content gap filling. For a detailed breakdown of what to track and when, the <a href="/geo-checklist/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO checklist</a> covers the measurement framework in full. If you would rather have the monitoring set up and managed for you, <a href="/geo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO services</a> from GEOoptimised include ongoing citation tracking as standard.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="faq" class="anchor-top">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-2" id="faq-accordion">
        {faqs.map(faq => (
          <div class="card overflow-hidden">
            <button
              type="button"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between p-5 text-left text-sm font-semibold text-white transition hover:bg-white/[.02]"
              aria-expanded="false"
            >
              <span>{faq.q}</span>
              <span class="faq-icon ml-4 shrink-0 text-[var(--accent)] transition-transform duration-200">+</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body max-h-0 overflow-hidden transition-[max-height] duration-300 ease-in-out">
              <p class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">{faq.a}</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <div class="mt-16" id="related">
        <span class="eyebrow">Related reading</span>
        <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-3">
          {related.map(item => (
            <a href={item.href} class="card card-hover block p-5 no-underline">
              <span class="eyebrow">{item.tag}</span>
              <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-base font-semibold text-white">{item.title}</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300">{item.excerpt}</p>
              <span class="mt-3 inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm text-[var(--accent)]">Read article <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></span>
            </a>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="relative border-t hair mt-12 overflow-hidden">
    <div class="dot-grid absolute inset-0 opacity-40" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="container-wide relative py-20 text-center">
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold grad-text md:text-4xl">Ready to Start Your GEO Programme?</h2>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-5 max-w-xl text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">
        We run the AI visibility audit, build the entity map, and deliver a prioritised 90-day plan with every step sequenced for your category and competitive landscape.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-col items-center gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:justify-center">
        <a href="/contact/" class="btn btn-primary">Book an AI visibility audit</a>
        <a href="/geo-services/" class="btn btn-ghost">Explore GEO services</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script>
    const faqBtns = document.querySelectorAll('#faq-accordion button');
    faqBtns.forEach(btn => {
      btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const body = btn.nextElementSibling as HTMLElement;
        const icon = btn.querySelector('.faq-icon') as HTMLElement;
        const open = btn.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
        btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', String(!open));
        if (open) {
          body.style.maxHeight = '0';
          icon.style.transform = 'rotate(0deg)';
        } else {
          body.style.maxHeight = body.scrollHeight + 'px';
          icon.style.transform = 'rotate(45deg)';
        }
      });
    });

    const tocLinks = document.querySelectorAll('#toc-nav a');
    const headings = Array.from(
      document.querySelectorAll('h2[id], h3[id]')
    ) as HTMLElement[];

    const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
      entries => {
        entries.forEach(entry => {
          if (entry.isIntersecting) {
            tocLinks.forEach(link => {
              link.classList.remove('text-[var(--accent)]');
              if (link.getAttribute('href') === '#' + entry.target.id) {
                link.classList.add('text-[var(--accent)]');
              }
            });
          }
        });
      },
      { rootMargin: '-20% 0px -70% 0px', threshold: 0 }
    );

    headings.forEach(h => observer.observe(h));
  </script>

